        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-14 15:02:04.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\nHow is the network-service object being modelled in SDC?",
        "patchset_number": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "8945a7e531bcad628ae6f6547bfdd85931dece15",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 33,
          "name": "James Forsyth",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jf2512@att.com",
          "username": "jimmydot"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-14 16:18:48.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\nIf these objects are not modelled in SDC, aai prefers the use of service-instance; service-type is already an attribute on the service-instance object. we can add a status attribute to service-instance unless orchestration-status is sufficient. we can add createdAt and updateAt attrs if needed to service-instance.  If the object is modelled in SDC, it seems like we should add the model attributes (at minimum, model-invariant-id and model-version-id)",
        "patchset_number": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "1e3abef0c73eea0daa2f03c1f0ceb4fd208beaed",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 141,
          "name": "maopeng zhang",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "zhang.maopeng1@zte.com.cn",
          "username": "maopengzhang"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-16 01:40:09.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\nIn the SDC, there are E2E service and network service in R1. SDC adds the network service and E2E service category in R1 and use the VFC import to define the network service properties and inputs.",
        "patchset_number": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "f21d47f021305f5d1a7e311b368950ff5338545d",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 879,
          "name": "subhash kumar singh",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "subh.singh@samsung.com",
          "username": "subhash_singh"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-16 12:00:04.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\n(1 comment)\n\nHello Maopeng, Could you please share reference for E2E service and network service in SDC. I will try to refer it.",
        "patchset_number": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "b59efd78f04f28557e5acbea3b7763a7d566e113",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 33,
          "name": "James Forsyth",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jf2512@att.com",
          "username": "jimmydot"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-18 12:30:57.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\n@maopeng, the point of the model-invariant-id, model-version-id on the service-instance is that using the SDC models it's possible to differentiate an E2E vs. Network service without creating a separate service-instance node type.  Is VF-C using the model attribute that correspond to the SDC model?  It doesn't seem so because you have not include the model attributes on the proposed network-service object.",
        "patchset_number": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "7f327fc4881db62aad3d5f3d18f2ccdf7bc3c4d1",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 33,
          "name": "James Forsyth",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jf2512@att.com",
          "username": "jimmydot"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-20 14:32:48.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\n@maopeng, what do you want to do with this one?",
        "patchset_number": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "8f721c97cbf1ee255797fb7dd8fc391145627005",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 141,
          "name": "maopeng zhang",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "zhang.maopeng1@zte.com.cn",
          "username": "maopengzhang"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-25 12:07:28.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\n@James, in R1, the NSDID is same with the service model UUID. VFC can get the NSDID via network service instanceid, and can get the related model infomation via NSDID. I think the NS service can include the NSD invariant ID and NSD version in the future as well, which can do more enhancements for the NSD and NS instance management, such as update, etc.",
        "patchset_number": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "f71844cabe471245685cca8a0abd0d5df289778f",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 141,
          "name": "maopeng zhang",
          "display_name": null,
